To end a C program, you can use the `exit()` function or the `return` statement.

1. `exit()` function:

The `exit()` function terminates the current process immediately. It takes an optional argument, which is the exit status of the process. Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    printf("Hello, World!\n");

    // Exit the program with a status of 0 (success)
    exit(0);

    // This line will never be executed
    printf("This will not be printed.\n");

    return 0;
}
```

